As we have seen,
the era in which Richard Wagner grew up,

3
00:00:13.346 --> 00:00:17.248
in the 19th century,
was a profoundly literary period.

4
00:00:17.248 --> 00:00:21.238
But while Berlioz and
Beethoven was reading Shakespeare,

5
00:00:21.238 --> 00:00:23.930
Wagner was reading Nordic mythology.

6
00:00:23.930 --> 00:00:27.735
Specifically he began to
read Das Niebelungenlied,

7
00:00:27.735 --> 00:00:29.683
the Song of the Nibelungs.

8
00:00:29.683 --> 00:00:36.140
A medieval legend that had been edited and
published in Modern German in the 1820's.

9
00:00:36.140 --> 00:00:38.520
Here is one of the original manuscripts.

10
00:00:38.520 --> 00:00:43.230
One from the early 13th century surviving
in a monastic library in Saint Gallen,

11
00:00:43.230 --> 00:00:43.900
Switzerland.

12
00:00:45.630 --> 00:00:51.430
And at that very moment that Wagner
was carried away with this fantasy,

13
00:00:51.430 --> 00:00:54.080
this fantasy Nordic literature,

14
00:00:54.080 --> 00:00:58.610
other Nordic literature was being
rediscovered and published.

15
00:00:58.610 --> 00:01:03.290
The Anglo Saxton Beowulf in
the Finnish Kalevala, for example.

16
00:01:04.310 --> 00:01:07.850
Wagner took the story of this legend,
the story of the Nibelungs and

17
00:01:07.850 --> 00:01:11.670
began to craft a libretto for an opera.

18
00:01:11.670 --> 00:01:17.370
Wagner's the only major composer
to have written his own librettos.

19
00:01:18.450 --> 00:01:22.370
So he wrote a libretto, but
then he found he needed to say more.

20
00:01:22.370 --> 00:01:27.780
He needed more explanation, so
he wrote another libretto, a prequel.

21
00:01:27.780 --> 00:01:33.960
And then a prequel to that prequel, and
then another until he had four librettos,

22
00:01:33.960 --> 00:01:38.080
a tetralogy which came to
be called The Ring Cycle.

23
00:01:39.480 --> 00:01:42.650
Here are the four operas
of the Ring Cycle.

24
00:01:43.720 --> 00:01:45.720
Why is it called the Ring Cycle?

25
00:01:46.770 --> 00:01:51.350
Because the story of the Nibelung
turns on the creation, the magic ring,

26
00:01:51.350 --> 00:01:55.700
the possession of which gives
its owner power over the world.

27
00:01:55.700 --> 00:01:57.929
If this all sounds familiar, it is.

28
00:01:59.300 --> 00:02:05.920
What we've got here is the beginning
of popular, Nordic fantasy literature.

29
00:02:05.920 --> 00:02:11.098
First in English translations
of the Song of the Nidelungs,

30
00:02:11.098 --> 00:02:15.810
and then in fantasy, elaborations,
as created by J.R.R.

31
00:02:15.810 --> 00:02:21.240
Tolkien, The Lord of the Ring,
CL Lewis, Chronicle of Narnia and

32
00:02:21.240 --> 00:02:26.720
more distantly, George Lucas's Star Wars,
George Martin's Game of Thrones.

33
00:02:26.720 --> 00:02:28.180
Wagner started it all.

34
00:02:29.270 --> 00:02:32.350
What's the plot of Wagner's Ring cycle?

35
00:02:32.350 --> 00:02:34.390
Well, it's complicated.

36
00:02:34.390 --> 00:02:38.310
With Wagner, every thing is
kind of long and complicated.

37
